isting test for embedded interpolated fragments within JSON strings or keys. I need to be cautious about compilation issues. \\n\\nMaybe I can check the existing class that's generated, but it seems like I can't do that. Instead, perhaps I should create a small test based on the documentation to build my confidence?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JSON interpolation in Scala**\\n\\nI'm considering whether using interpolated raw JSON object members is possible, like `json\\\"\\\"\\\"{\\\"a\\\":1}\\\"\\\"\\\"` and `json\\\"\\\"\\\"{$fields, \\\"b\\\": 2}\\\"\\\"\\\"`. It might not be valid JSON syntax. Testing unicode escapes could help though. I need all top-level test classes to be public, and Scala class defaults are okay for that. I'll have to check my build.gradle dependencies for circe-parser while adding or adjusting methods in my test file. It's a bit of a puzzle!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_q5RXWglrjKwNBWB321wwaPJ0|fc_090ecef0820ad37d016a3fa671783c8195af8278e59d17a573", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/build.gradle"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 965, "output": 686, "cacheRead": 23552, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 25203, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782556258423, "responseId": "resp_090ecef0820ad37d016a3fa663015c8195ade3603284eb4c15"}}
